Prion diseases or transmissible spongiform encephalopathies
(TSEs)1 are a group of
neurodegenerative diseases affecting both animals and humans (1). Such
disorders include scrapie in sheep, bovine spongiform encephalopathy in
cattle, and Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD),
Gerstmann-Straussler-Scheinker syndrome, and fatal familial insomnia in humans (2, 3). TSEs may be of sporadic, genetic, or
infectious origin, and the agent believed to be responsible for these
disorders is a protein molecule termed PrPSc
